  "text": "Node.js implements comprehensive input validation and command injection prevention for the child_process module through a multi-layer defense mechanism spanning JavaScript and C++. The entry points for spawning child processes are the public API functions: exec(), execFile(), spawn(), fork(), and their synchronous counterparts (execSync, execFileSync, spawnSync) defined in lib/child_process.js.\n\nAll command/file string inputs are validated for null bytes using the validateArgumentNullCheck() function (lib/child_process.js:963), which checks if a string contains the null byte character ('\\u0000') and throws an ERR_INVALID_ARG_VALUE error if detected. This prevents null-byte injection attacks where attackers could use null bytes to truncate filenames and inject alternate commands.\n\nThe normalizeSpawnArguments() function (lib/child_process.js:538) serves as the central validation hub for spawn operations, performing comprehensive input sanitization including:\n- Null-byte validation for the file parameter (line 540)\n- Null-byte validation for all args array elements via validateArgumentsNullCheck() (line 556)\n- Null-byte validation for argv0 option (line 597)\n- Null-byte validation for shell option parameter (line 613)\n- Null-byte validation for environment variable keys and values (lines 691-692)\n- Null-byte validation for execPath and execArgv in fork() (lines 142, 146)\n\nThe normalizeExecArgs() function (lib/child_process.js:188) validates the command string for null bytes and is called by exec(), ensuring shell-invoked commands cannot contain null bytes.\n\nAll spawn variations route through the internal ChildProcess class (lib/internal/child_process.js:254), which wraps the native Process binding. The ChildProcess.spawn() method (lib/internal/child_process.js:354) calls the native C++ ProcessWrap.spawn() method after validation.\n\nThe C++ ProcessWrap class (src/process_wrap.cc:51) is the native binding that interfaces with libuv for actual process spawning. The Spawn() method (src/process_wrap.cc:153) performs additional checks, including permission validation via THROW_IF_INSUFFICIENT_PERMISSIONS (line 158-159), and prepares the uv_process_options_t structure with validated parameters.\n\nThe ParseStdioOptions() method (src/process_wrap.cc:110) handles stdio stream setup, while the Kill() method (src/process_wrap.cc:312) manages process termination. Environment variables are converted to C-style strings (lines 243-250), arguments are duplicated safely via strdup() (line 221), and all memory is properly freed after process initialization (lines 297-307).\n\nThe permission system enforces child_process access controls through ChildProcessPermission class (src/permission/child_process_permission.h), checked at the native layer before spawning.\n\nSynchronous spawning (spawnSync via src/spawn_sync.cc) follows the same validation path through normalizeSpawnArguments() before delegating to native code.\n\nThis layered approach—JavaScript-level string validation for null bytes, argument array validation, environment variable pair validation, followed by native C++ validation and permission checks—creates comprehensive protection against command injection attacks in child process operations."
}

